A Brown Creeper foraging in a ponderosa pine. This is the same bird as in XC212529.

Little later saw a bird roughly sparrow-sized, maybe a bit larger, with brownish upper wings and bright (white/gray/beige) underside.  When the bird flew up, it turned south-east and flew a longer distance away (too far to further track it with binoculars), so it did not stay in the area.  This might have been the bird in the recording but maybe it was a different bird.

We observed European Stonechats (Saxicola Rubicola) and Corn buntings (Emberiza calandra) around the same time in the same habitat.

Habitat is a renatured old mining waste site dump, with wild grass and partly overgrown with some lower bush vegetation e.g. oak and beech tree bushes and other small bushes.

Bright blue sky, sunny, around 5pm, one hour before sunset.

Recorded in lowland area, in a fragment of Atlantic Forest of Cocalzinho adjacent to Serra dos Pireneus. The species vocalized in a hillside forest, humid and high, with high presence of Euterpe edulis. It was responding to the playback of Ramphastos Dicolorus, and approached, shutting himself minutes later and not vocalizing anymore. I believe it is this species because its occurrence is dated to the region by WCS, and there is a collection made by J. Hidasi in 1970 near the capital Goiânia. It is a new documentation for the region with real proof, although there are reports of this species in the locality.

Différents exemples d'effets indésirables de l'écho rassemblés ici en un son. Tout d'abord deux cris de Petits Gravelots, qui sont chacun dédoublés. 
Puis un cri de Foulque macroule, dédoublé aussi. 
Ensuite un cri de Chouette hulotte qui est à la fois dédoublé mais surtout rendu indistinct par les traînées dues elles aussi à l'écho (cette fois-ci dans un milieu "trop" boisé"). 
Enfin un cri de Rougegorge familier où l'on voit de même des traînées (idem, milieu "trop" boisé").
